s. With particular relevance to the period, Persiles questions the issue of cultural pluralism in the Spanish empire and emphasizes the need to rethink the radically altered category of lo bárbaro/the barbarian (which included not only the Jew, the Muslim, and the Gypsy, but also the criollo, the mestizo, and the indiano), a new multiracial and multiethnic reality that posed a profound challenge to early modern Spain. The contributors offer a range of perspectives in spatial theory, psychology and subjectivity, visual culture, and literary theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEpic literature, SpanishxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aCervantes.  aDon Quixote.  aHeliodorus.  aPersiles.  aRenaissance.  aancient.  aearly modern Spain.  aliterary criticism.  aliterature.  anovel.  aromance.1 aAlbalá Pelegrín, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmas, Frederick A. de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong-Roche, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownlee, Marina S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCascardi, Anthony J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastillo, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilders, William P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgginton, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenaghan, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLezra, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLozano-Renieblas, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular